[start section id="20112"]

I carefully discussed with the patient and his wife the natural history of colorectal cancer with particular emphasis to what happens to patients with lymph node-positive disease; more so, with more than 10 lymph nodes involved by metastasis.  I also showed him data from the adjuvant web page, including that of survival with or without chemotherapy, using a regimen like FOLFOX or a regimen like Xeloda alone.
I believe that Mr. Kelly has a high-risk of developing metastasis and that he is otherwise a very healthy 68-year-old male.  My recommendation is for him to receive chemotherapy.  We discussed that chemotherapy can cause temporary immunosuppression, short, caused by neutropenia.  This may or may not happen with the doses of chemotherapy that he will receive.  He is on chronic immunosuppression of a different nature.  We discussed the difference between immunosuppression caused by chemotherapy for colon cancer versus immunosuppression to prevent transplant rejection.
We discussed potential side-effects of chemotherapy including nausea, vomiting, alopecia, neuropathy, fatigue, skin rash, cytopenias, infections, or bleeding.
I had the opportunity to discuss my consultation with Dr. Leslie Howell, from Cardiology Transplant.  Our colleagues will meet as a group to see if this is prudent or not to use adjuvant chemotherapy for colon cancer in the setting of chronic immunosuppression.
I think that a regimen using Xeloda plus oxaliplatin will be a good balance and adequate adjuvant chemotherapy with dosing that is easy to adjust and not requiring the placement of a Port-a-Cath.
I will see the patient in follow-up in approximately one-week.  At that time, I plan to start chemotherapy unless Cardiology has a different opinion.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

